VIII. The Laccdaemonians, aud at first the Athenians, claimed

no authority over the cities which they had conquered: only they required them to have a constitution like their own 3 the Lacedaemo- nians, an aristocracy, the Atheniens, a democracy, as we learn from Thucydides, Isocrates, Demosthenes, and Aristotle. Of these two characters who constantly disturbed Greece, Aristocracy and Demo- cracy, an old comedian, Heniochus, speaks, as women. So Artabanus, in Tacitus, established an aristocracy at Seleucia. Whether such changes add to the victor’s secursty, is not a matter for our con- sideration.
